hoodMarket: The North Hardy Toll Road’s location between the heavily trafficked Interstate 10 and Beltway 8, as well as its proximity to the George Bush Intercontinental Airport, makes it well positioned to satisfy demand generated by the nearby population growth. ,Since 2010, more than 80% of Harris County's population growth has occurred in its unincorporated areas. The majority immediately to the west and increasingly the east of the submarket, especially with the completion of the Grand Parkway. The North Hardy Toll Road also benefits from rooftop growth in Montgomery County to the north, particularly Springwoods Village, The Woodlands, and Conroe. The area draws distribution tenants looking to be close to the fastest-growing population region in Houston and in a newer stock of buildings. ,The area’s industrial inventory has grown by nearly 50% since 2010. Yet vacancies remain relatively low. Among the largest recent developments, Grocers Supply and Conn’s HomePlus moved into their build-to-suits in the area recently. And DB Schenker moved into its new distribution location nearby. Distribution tenants tend to prefer buildings with higher clear heights, stronger load bearing walls, and larger truck bays.,Rents in the North Hardy Toll area are below neighboring areas, particularly to the north and west.
propOverview: Presidents Park is Houston's newest and most flexible master-planned industrial project.  The first installment, Presidents Park 5, is currently under construction and is expected to be completed in Q2 2020.  This speculative building can suit either single or multi-tenant needs with glass storefront entrances on both ends and ample auto and trailer parking.  The state-of-the-art, front-load space will have 32' clear height, a modern 185' truck court, LED interior and exterior lights, and ESFR sprinklers.  The park itself is undergoing major infrastructure improvements including upgrading and expanding Milner Road for easier and quicker access in and out of the park. Presidents Park’s strategic location in north Houston, immediately south of IAH Airport, provides unmatched access to the ever-growing Houston MSA population and business centers. The park is located less than 5 miles from all three major north/south arteries, including I-45, Hardy Toll Road and Hwy 59, and boasts immediate access to Beltway 8 and a 10-minute drive to the 610 Loop for excellent circulation around the city of Houston. This key location combined with Presidents Park’s best-in-class design and state-of-the-art facilities creates an ideal setting for future growth.

hoodMarket: Supported by its central location and bracketed by several arterial freeways, Sorrento Mesa’s profile has taken off in recent years. The neighborhood provides plentiful housing and is within close proximity to high-end shopping, restaurants, and San Diego’s crystalline beaches. Sorrento Mesa’s employers recruit from the pipeline of students graduating from neighboring UC San Diego. High household incomes and advanced education levels are common among residents here.,While Sorrento Mesa was dependent on Qualcomm, its lineup of industrial tenants has diversified significantly over the past several years. Along with UTC and Torrey Pines, Sorrento Mesa has become one of San Diego’s core innovation hubs and includes notable tenants such as Qualcomm, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Meggitt Polymers, CV Sciences, and Quidel Corporation, among others. Green Flash, one of San Diego’s most prominent brewers, also calls Sorrento Mesa home.,Although the vacancy rate is susceptible to significant swings due to large industrial tenants, demand remains firmly locked in place for one of San Diego’s most desirable neighborhoods for industrial tenants. And while rent levels are among the highest in San Diego, they still offer a discount compared with more coastal industrial areas such as Torrey Pines or UTC.
propOverview: 10015 Waples Court is located in Sorrento Valley which was originally designed as San Diego's industrial district and paved the way for several well-known corporations and industries to headquarter there, such as Qualcomm, Dexcom, Arena Pharmaceuticals, and Accelrys US. Due to the short 15-minute drive to the University of California in San Diego, Sorrento Valley organically strayed from the original growth plan and has since become a desirable destination for residents, which provides businesses with a strong industrial infrastructure and a built-in labor force. Recognized as one of the leading high-tech hubs in the US, San Diego’s innovation economy is anchored by established companies such as Intel, Sony, and Hewlett Packard. San Diego is home to the largest concentration of military in the world, the largest federal military workforce in the nation, and some of the world’s largest research and development companies. Given the highly-skilled workforce, robust training programs, and proximity to Mexico, San Diego is also a hub for advanced manufacturing companies. In addition, the 1,100 life sciences companies and more than 80 research institutes are major drivers of the innovative local economy. 10015 Waples Court is located a half-mile off Mira Mesa Boulevard, the main thoroughfare through the industrial parks of Sorrento Valley, and provides easy access to major transportation routes with a 5-minute drive to I-805 and 10 minutes to I-5. The Port of San Diego is a 30-minute drive and oversees two major cargo terminals, the 96-acre Tenth Avenue Marine Terminal and the 135-acre National City Marine Terminal. 10015 Waples Court is under new ownership with modernizing renovations underway featuring 9,200 square feet of new, highly upgraded office space, 12 large grade-level doors, 9 dock positions, ESFR sprinkler system, and skylights. The facility boasts 31'-33' clear heights and 1,200 amps of 277/480 volt power with a 3-phase/4-wire system.

propOverview: Located in the heart of the San Francisco Bay Area, 4225 Hacienda Drive is the Tri-Valley’s premier warehouse, distribution, and regional headquarters facility. This multi-tenanted building is comprised of 389,673 square feet on a 22.38-acre parcel in the Hacienda Business Park. The building features a new roof, 28’-30’ interior clear heights, 41 dock-high doors that measure 8’x10’, and two grade-level doors, making it an ideal property for logistics-focused companies. Additionally, the building offers 2,800-amp, 277/480-volt, 3-phase power, forklift charging stations, and an in-place exhaust system. 4225 Hacienda Drive is well-positioned for any business serving local customers and on the West Coast. Three freeway intersections directly serve the Hacienda Business Park: two off I-580, and one off nearby I-680, giving the site the best freeway access of any business center in the Bay Area. The property is located just 20 miles from the California Central Valley, 30 minutes from the Port of Oakland, 51 minutes from the Port of Redwood City, 26 minutes from the Quality Transport, Inc. rail line in Fremont, and within 30 miles of both the Oakland and the San Jose International Airports. The location also offers many commute benefits because of its reverse-commute location and proximity to the Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) system, with trains arriving every 15 minutes during peak travel hours. Many companies have already located their businesses in this desirable area, and corporate neighbors for 4225 Hacienda Drive include Boeing, Integen, Bio-Rad, and Roche.

hoodMarket: Paramount is a small city in southern Los Angeles County, just north of Long Beach. Interstate 710, the main highway link to the massive twin ports of Los Angeles and Long Beach, forms the western edge of the city, and Interstate 105 runs east-west through the northern portion. This is a dense, built-out section of Los Angeles, with an industrial hub nestled between several residential neighborhoods. ,The local economy is primarily comprised of small businesses, although a few major industrial operations dot the landscape. Ralphs owns a 550,000-square-foot distribution center in the center of town, and aerospace manufacturers Carlton Forge Works and Castle Metals Aerospace have their primary facilities here as well. ,As in much of Los Angeles, the heavily built-out character of the area prevents any significant new industrial development. Vacancies remain low as a result, although industrial space here is available for a slight discount compared to the greater Los Angeles average.
propOverview: Located adjacent to an established industrial sector in Paramount, 7110 Rosecrans Avenue provides amenities typically reserved for office users, all while enjoying easy accessibility to the area’s major highways. Recent major renovations include both interior and exterior upgrades. Brand new, two-story office space offers a spacious conference room, open, customizable workspace, and partitioned areas that overlook the loading docks. Loading options include two drive-in doors, one at the front of the warehouse and one at the back, and two interior, dock-high positions that offer a covered truck well. The building also features a 24’ clear height, 100 amps of 120/208-volt, 3-phase, 4-wire power with options to expand up to 1,000 amps, new LED lighting, new ESFR sprinklers, and a shared 6,000 square-foot covered storage/yard area that is completely fenced. Commutability and distribution options include just a 5-minute drive to both the 105 and 710 freeways and a 10-minute drive to the 605 and 91 freeways. The Long Beach-Daugherty Field Airport can be reached in 14 minutes, the Los Angeles International Airport in 22, and the Titan Terminal and Transport, Inc. rail line in just 11, providing further conveniences for a variety of industrial uses. For dining and entertainment, employees enjoy multiple options in less than a mile walk, including El Compa Restaurant, Tortas Chingonas, Taqueria 2 Amigos, and the Paramount Entertainment Center, featuring the daily Paramount Swap Meet and the Paramount Drive-In Theatres. This prime Paramount location offers access to 16-million citizens within 50 miles.

hoodMarket: Berkeley County benefits from an abundance of developable land, readily available labor and close proximity to The Port of Charleston. Transportation is made easy here through Interstate 26, which provides quick access to the port, Interstate 95, and South Carolina’s capital, Columbia.,The Port of Charleston continues to increase TEU handling capabilities, making Charleston an attractive option for major industrial users. In fact, the port recently secured federal funding to deepen the harbor to 52 feet, making it one of the deepest ports on the east coast by 2021. This advantage has attracted notable industrial users in recent years. For instance, Volvo opened its first North American plant in Ridgeville in 2018 which sparked both development and demand for industrial assets in the area. ,Industrial properties are largely concentrated along the I-26 corridor, where the percentage of college graduates is higher and drive times to the Port of Charleston are shorter. Parts suppliers for some of North Charleston’s largest manufacturers such as Boeing and Mercedes Benz are located in this corridor as well. ,Although Berkeley County is home to an impressive portfolio of industrial users, rents here are comparatively inexpensive. According to CoStar data, properties here rent at a discount compared to its neighbor North Charleston, despite close proximity. Rents here are also more affordable than the average rate seen metro wide.

The major artery between New York and Eastern Long Island, the Long Island Expressway, traverses the area, making it easily accessible to both Long Island and New York City. ,Industrial tenants in Central Queens are able to service the largest metropolitan area in the county.The area is a prime location for last-mile distribution hubs, given the proximity to New York‘s major airports. Large tenants here represent industries ranging from transportation and storage to food and restaurant services. UPS moved into a 475,000-square-foot facility in 2018, and are now the largest industrial occupier in the submarket. ,Compared to other locales with similar access to Manhattan and other New York City boroughs, rents in Central Queens are more affordable. Despite being well located in the country’s largest metropolitan area, construction in Central Queens has been limited, with no major developments opening in past few years. Lack of available space in this dense urban area has contributed to the lack of new construction.

Central location between two major truck routes, with access to Brooklyn, Queens, Manhattan and the Bronx via the BQE, LIE and all bridges and tunnels. The building features new capital improvements, including new floors, exterior facade, re-paved parking & roof, making 5700 49th Place a truly rare industrial asset in the boroughs of New York City.

hoodMarket: One of Orlando’s largest industrial markets, Northwest Orange County stretches from Downtown Orlando to Lake Apopka to the west and runs north along Interstate 4 to Maitland Boulevard. Asking rents here vary across the relatively large geographical area, with properties closer to Interstate 4 renting at a premium. Overall, industrial rents are significantly lower than those in Seminole County directly to the east.,Industrial tenants benefit from accessibility to Central Florida as well as points west, north, and south. Interstate 4 runs as far west as Tampa and north to Daytona Beach, where it meets with the major north-south connector Interstate 95. Some of the largest industrial tenants in the area include Winn-Dixie, Sysco Corporation, and Coca Cola.,Another key thoroughfare is Orange Blossom Trail (U.S. 441), along which many of the area’s largest industrial properties are dotted. The road, which bisects the northwestern quadrant of Orange County, runs south through Kissimmee into Miami and north through Ocala and Gainesville to Georgia.

hoodMarket: Eastern Nassau is centrally located in Long Island, with easy access to Kennedy and LaGuardia airports as well as important transportation nodes providing access throughout the region. Specifically within the Hicksville Triangle, which stretches from Westbury to Plainview and then up to Jericho, there are several important transit hubs and intersections located here. These include the Jericho Turnpike-Long Island Expressway intersection, the Newbridge Road and Northern State Parkway thoroughfares, and several Long Island Railroad (LIRR) stations. ,The area has benefitted from the continued growth of e-commerce and expansion of ‘last-mile’ distribution hubs. Other than logistics services, the area features a strong occupier landscape ranging a variety of industries from food & restaurant services to moving & storage. For example, Amazon, Sub Zero Group, Nassau Candy are some of the largest tenants here. ,Available space is a sought after commodity, as few new projects have delivered in recent years. Steady demand and limited supply should assure that this well-located market remains competitive.

hoodMarket: The Northeast Dallas area is a well-established, in-town industrial center in the metroplex. The area is diverse and can be segmented by areas inside LBJ Freeway and outside LBJ Freeway. The largest concentration of industrial tenants fall outside of LBJ Freeway towards Garland. An outer ring suburb, Garland is one of Dallas-Fort Worth’s original boomburbs, with heavy concentrations of industrial employment and blue-collar employment base. ,Geography and transportation are strategic considerations for tenants in this part of Dallas. The area includes primary transportation arteries: the LBJ Freeway, U.S. 75 North, and in the outer section, President George Bush Tollway. The existing tenant base includes manufacturing firms, retail and wholesalers, and transportation. The largest tenants include Kraft Foods, which has a large manufacturing location in Garland; home goods store At Home, which has a large distribution facility; and watch retailer Fossil, which has space near its corporate headquarters in Richardson.,With one of the largest existing inventories of industrial buildings, new construction in Northeast Dallas has been limited compared to other rapidly growing areas of Dallas-Fort Worth. Largely built-out, available land is the biggest constraint for new buildings.,Given excellent highway and rail access, robust leasing activity is keeping vacancies low. Rental rates are on par with the Dallas-Fort Worth average.
propOverview: Right on the outskirts of Dallas, 1501 Kings Road in Garland, Texas, presents a large built-out industrial facility with excess land big enough for future expansion. The 154,968 square-foot warehouse is configured to accommodate both a single business or multiple businesses, with an 85,968 square-foot warehouse, a 66,548 square-foot warehouse, and a 1,878 square-foot office/maintenance shop. The larger warehouse section features 31’ clear height, 14 8’x10’ dock-high doors with levelers and seals included, and one dock-high door with a metal ramp. The smaller warehouse section offers 15’ clear heights with the option to expand to 31’, ten 8’x10’ dock-high doors with levelers and seals included, and the office/maintenance shop space. The entire facility is 100% sprinklered and air-conditioned and features 480-volt, 3-phase, 4-wire power at 3,000 amps, 24’x36’ column spacing, a secured truck court, and ample car and trailer parking. The option also exists to secure the entire site fully. The additional 5.77 acres on the parcel could be used for building expansion, but also lends well to parking, trailer storage, or outside storage. 1501 Kings Road is positioned just five minutes from I-635/Lyndon B Johnson Freeway, which conveniently connects to the surrounding major highways. There is also an active rail line located seven minutes away, the Dallas Love Field Airport is 29 minutes away, and the Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport is just 37 minutes away. Businesses enjoy access to a sizable employee base as the building is 10 minutes from downtown Garland and only 22 minutes from downtown Dallas.

hoodMarket: Orange County is one of the northernmost counties in the New York metropolitan area, located about 50 miles northwest of Manhattan. The stock here largely consists of warehouses with less than 50,000 square feet of rentable building area. Properties larger than 100,000 square feet are primarily concentrated in Middletown, Montgomery, Newburgh, and Port Jervis.,Orange County has an advantageous location within comfortable driving distance of some of the country’s largest population centers. New York can be reached within two hours, Philadelphia within three hours, and Boston within four hours. Several major highways run through here, including The New York State Thruway running north-south and I-84 running east-west. Orange County is also home to the New York Stewart International Airport in New Windsor. The airport carries FedEx, UPS, and Kalitta Air cargo lines to seven domestic destinations.,The county is largely landlocked, except for an eastern border with the Hudson River. Much of the inventory in Newburgh is located near the Hudson, where goods can be shipped up to Albany and beyond and down to Port Newark-Elizabeth Marine Terminal. More than 15 million tons of cargo is reportedly shipped in a typical year between New York and Waterford, which is 11 miles north of Albany.,Orange County has many tenants with footprints larger than 100,000 square feet. Several retailers base large shipping operations here, including Amscan, Home Depot, and Staples. There’s also a notable manufacturing presence, from the likes of Ball Metal Beverage Container Corporation, Takasago International, and PharmaCann, among many other companies.
propOverview: 334 County Route 49 presents an excellent manufacturing or warehouse opportunity with a prime Hudson Valley location positioned on a 12.7-acre lot. Situated just five minutes from I-84, the property features a steel façade with three exterior loading docks complete with levelators, two drive-in doors, two truck wells, a 10-ton freight elevator, 14’ clear heights throughout, 25’x25’ column spacing, and 4000 amps of three-phase power with on-site backup generators in place. There is ample built-out office space featuring modern finishes, including floor-to-ceiling windows on partitioned offices, multiple reception areas, and conference rooms. The spacious parking lot features 126 spots for employees and guests, and the site also boasts a private helipad. Complementing the short drive to I-84, distribution options include just a 38-minute drive to the Stewart International Airport and a 99-minute drive to the Port Newark Container Terminal. A 7-minute drive reaches the downtown Middletown area, offering employees numerous restaurants, breweries, and conveniences options for dining, drinking, and errands. 47,330 citizens within a 5-mile radius offer a vast labor pool and round out the abundance of amenities at this location.

propOverview: Situated on a 7.3-acre business park in the desirable Near Northwest submarket, 6507 West Little York Road offers amenities and conveniences to meet the needs of today’s industrial tenants. The Northwest Place Industrial Park features five attractive, tilt-wall facilities and a fully curbed and nicely landscaped access road that connects Bingle and West Little York Roads. 6507 West Little York boasts a rare drive-thru opportunity with 2 (two) 12’x12’ and 2 (two) 16’x16’ grade-level, over-sized roll-up doors. The building also offers the capability for a 10-ton crane, and there is currently a high-pile permit in place for storage. Other features include divisibility down to 9,000 square feet, 3,737 square feet of office space, a 24’ eave height, two warehouse exhaust fans, T-5 high-bay fluorescent light fixtures throughout the warehouse, 480volt, 3-phase, 400 amp power, exterior wall pack lighting, and a controlled-mode ELO sprinkler system in place. The site offers ample outside storage and employee parking options, and from the connecting road commuters, customers and cargo alike enjoy easy access to the nearby major highways. Both I-45 and I-10 are reached in 15 minutes or less, and from there, three major airports can be reached in an hour drive or less. The Houston George Bush Intercontinental Airport is 26 minutes from the site, the William P Hobby Airport is 41, and the Ellington Field Airport is 54. It is also only a 30-minute drive to the Port of Houston and an 8-minute drive to the Tencon Industries, Inc rail line. The Near Northwest industrial submarket has experienced low vacancy rates and strong demand for space over the past few years. With no reported industrial space under construction as of the end of 2019, 6507 West Little York Road offers an excellent opportunity for tenants to locate their business in this area.

hoodMarket: In the age of e-commerce and just in time logistics, moving goods to consumers has become increasingly important. Known as West D-FW Airport, the industrial zone on the western side of Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport is among the few places in North Texas that provides that value. It’s located in one of America's fastest-growing cities near interstates paired with unparalleled international and domestic connectivity from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport. ,The airport has made a concerted effort to increase its industrial offering in the past few years. As a result, the total tonnage has grown by double digits, and new cargo carriers now serve the area. In addition to the accessibility to global markets, many of the properties and developable land fall within the airport's Foreign Trade Zone. Companies operating in this area receive numerous inventory tax exemptions for international inventory. They benefit from reduced customs duties, tariffs, and taxes, potentially saving companies millions of dollars while providing direct airport ramp access and reducing shipping times.,West D-FW Airport’s vacancy rates typically track lower than the rest of Dallas-Fort Worth Because of the numerous advantages of this location, rents are usually higher than in many other industrial nodes. However, higher rents have not slowed leasing activity, which has remained strong in West D-FW Airport throughout this economic expansion.

hoodMarket: In just the past five years, Salem County has seen a surge in leasing by ecommerce platforms, third party logistics firms, and general retailers opening large distribution facilities from which to ship goods throughout the mid-Atlantic. ,Thanks to Salem County’s abundance of open land and ease of new construction, large newly delivered distribution facilities rent at significant discounts to those in Northern New Jersey. But via the New Jersey Turnpike, New York City is just a two hour drive from Salem County, and major population centers in Philadelphia and Washington D.C. are an even shorter trip. ,These benefits have attracted firms including Jet.com, Five Below, and UPS to open new distribution facilities ranging from 250,000 to 1 million square feet since 2015. ,Most of Salem County’s industrial properties are also less than a 15-mile drive from the Port of Wilmington, which handles more imports of fresh fruit and juice concentrates than any other port in North America. New Jersey also ranks among the top five U.S. states for production of crops including Blueberries, Cranberries, Peaches, and Bell Peppers with most of these goods being produced in the southern half of the state.,The area’s booming agricultural sector has helped to attract major food sellers and distributors to Salem County including Goya Foods of South Jersey, which operates and 200,000 square feet distribution center here, along with Argo Merchants which occupies more than 1.1 million square feet of industrial space in Salem County.
propOverview: The newest building in an established business park offers prime warehouse, manufacturing, and distribution opportunities. The Gateway Business Park is a master-planned distribution park consisting of 407 acres, and the Gateway Business Park – East is part of the second phase of the development and features 143 acres and an additional million square feet of industrial space. 1 Sorbello Road has been constructed so that the building itself is complete, but the interior is ready for a rapid build-out based on a tenant’s needs. A 20-year PILOT tax abatement is in place, and real estate taxes of $0.40 per-square-foot (with modest increases) provide significant cost savings over the term of a lease. The building features a 36’ height, 50’ x 50’ column spacing, ample trailer parking options, and nearly immediate access to I-295, the toll-free interstate that runs parallel to the New Jersey Turnpike, in less than a mile drive. Many major corporations are already benefitting from the desirable accessibility options the Gateway Business Park provides, including Goya Foods, Berkowitz Glass, UPS, and Jet.com. The Delaware Memorial Bridge is only seven miles from the center, and the Commodore Barry Bridge is only eight. With easy access to Philadelphia, Wilmington, and Baltimore, the Gateway Business Park also boasts a highly central location being just an overnight drive to one-third of the nation’s population. The Philadephia International Airport and the Wilmington Philadelphia Regional Airport are just a 24-minute and a 16-minute drive, respectively, providing further distribution options for freight. The Gateway Business Park – East is being developed by Matrix, one of the Northeast’s most respected real estate investment and development firms.

hoodMarket: Bordering Lake Michigan and comprising many of Chicago’s most affluent zip codes, Northern Cook County consists of a cluster of densely packed communities with tree lined streets and top-ranked school districts. Northern Cook County is also home to Northwestern University and its nationally ranked medical program, which helps support the local economy. A dense network of medical and research facilities and a well-established biopharmaceutical industry contribute to Northwestern University’s broader business-oriented ecosystem. . ,The area boasts an abundance of parks and greenspace, while being served by a plethora of shopping and eating destinations scattered throughout the popular areas of Evanston and Glenview. High-quality school districts, a nationally recognized university, and a robust local economy combine to create a vibrant community environment in Northern Cook County, which continues to attract both workers and businesses alike.   ,Manufacturers and logistics companies are drawn to North Cook County in part due to its accessibility, with its well-connected network of interstates providing access to over 10 million people and one of the nation’s busiest ports. In addition to connectivity and density, the area’s highly educated workforce and network of existing employers appeals to office and industrial users. Many small and mid-sized companies establish locally-oriented industrial operations here. For example, a variety of companies throughout the area are focused on durable and non-durable goods wholesaling, as well as printing, HVAC, plumbing, construction or commercial printing, all of which benefit from the area’s dense, infill location. ,Given its unbeatable accessibility, diverse workforce, and local industry drivers, the Northern Cook County industrial area continues to attract new tenants in droves. As a result, available space has declined it’s the lowest level in 15 years.  Moreover, properties containing research, manufacturing or other specialized industrial space are nearly fully occupied. With such tight availability and strong tenant demand, industrial rents throughout this area will continue to experience upward pressure.

Located only 14 miles north from downtown Chicago and minutes from beautiful Lake Michigan, the city of Lincolnwood is an ethnically diverse community that appeals to many for its things to do and see. The property is located near many shops, parks, and eateries, within walking distance of the Lincolnwood Town Center and Lincolnwood Centennial Park. After work happy hours or lunch break strolls with coworkers can become a routine with this sought-after location as your next workspace.

hoodMarket: Delaware County is an affluent community in the Columbus metro area, situated just north of downtown and Ohio State University. The area features a large, highly educated population, with over 200,000 residents, 54% of which have a bachelor’s degree or higher. In addition, the county is home to one of Ohio’s top private liberal arts colleges – Ohio Wesleyan University.,The area offers easy access to multiple interstates, including 270, 71, 70, U.S. 23, and U.S. 33. With central Ohio being within a day’s drive to 65% of the U.S. and Canadian populations, logistics providers and companies seeking a strong regional distribution hub have taken notice. DHL, Kroger, McGraw-Hill Education, Advance Auto Parts, and JEGS High Performance are just a few of the companies operating distribution centers in Delaware County.,JP Morgan is Delaware County’s largest private sector employer, with just over 10,000 employees, followed by Anthem Blue Cross and Blue Shield, with 900 local employees. The area is also home to a wealth of retail and entertainment offerings, including the world famous Columbus Zoo and Aquarium and one of the area’s largest shopping destinations, Polaris Fashion Place.
propOverview: The Property is strategically located in the Delaware County Submarket, providing users excellent proximity to Highways 36, 42, and 23, which in turn provide accessibility to the Interstate 270 loop and connectivity to Interstates 70 and 71. The Property is located in the main industrial pocket within the City of Delaware, which drives the largest user demand in the area. With easy access to I-270, I-71, I-70, US 23 and US 33 providing multi-directional interstate highway connectivity and being a one-day drive to more than 65% of the US and Canadian populations, Central Ohio has become one of the most active distribution hubs in the country. The property is functionally designed with convenient accessibility, appropriate truck court depths, trailer parking and auto parking, allowing for maximum tenant demand. The property was constructed in 1996 with market-leading clear heights (33’) that meet and exceed user demand. The building sits on a 26-acre site with a full fence surrounding the 150’ deep truck court. There is T5 High Output lighting in the warehouse space equipped with motion sensors, and secured outdoor lighting to make sure employees feel safe on the grounds at all times. The property owner is also offering various signage opportunities to enhance your company brand along Pittsburgh Drive.  Users also enjoy access to a deep labor pool concentrated on the north end of Columbus and beyond.

hoodMarket: Santa Clarita is situated at the northern extreme of the Los Angeles metro area. Mountainous geography separates the region from the L.A. basin’s notorious suburban sprawl, giving it a somewhat secluded feel, and Downtown Los Angeles is an hour’s drive away on a good day. The region straddles I-5, California’s main north-south artery, giving it a desirable location for logistics operations moving goods from the ports of Long Beach and Los Angeles up the West Coast to Northern California and the Pacific Northwest.,Most industrial activity is concentrated north of the Santa Clarita River in close proximity to I-5. Third-party logistics companies comprise a major portion of the tenant base, with a mix of light manufacturing operations and support services for L.A.’s massive entertainment industry.,In comparison to the rest of L.A.’s drum-tight industrial market, tenants here may find a few more availabilities. This is one of the last corners of the region with significant amounts of raw, developable land, and speculative construction is more prevalent here than almost anywhere else in the county.,Santa Clarita’s distance from the ports and heart of the metro limits the appeal for regional last-mile distribution operations. Industrial rents tend to be more affordable than in more centrally located industrial hubs. However, the area’s strategic position as the last sizable community along I-5 before departing L.A County to points north helps to underpin demand and continues to draw the attention of developers and investors.
propOverview: 29003 Avenue Sherman is a state-of-the-art industrial facility located within the prestigious Valencia Commerce Center. The impressive building was recently renovated, featuring sleek designs and premium finishes, creating a headquarters atmosphere and adding a plethora of on-site amenities. The immaculate 11,799-square-foot office features a two-story reception area complete with stone tile floors and a furnished waiting area, a staff lounge with a kitchen and exercise room on the first floor, and a break room with a coffee bar on the second floor. There are three large bullpens, a conference room, private restrooms with showers, a lunch patio, and nine private offices, four of which are on the second floor overlooking the warehouse. The expansive 56,324-square-foot warehouse boasts 26' to 28' clear heights and 2,000 amps of 480-volt, 3-phase, 4-wire power. Exceptional loading is provided with two 12' by 14' ground-level doors and four 9' by 14' dock-high doors, with the ability to add a fifth dock to rapidly accommodate any arising need. 29003 Avenue Sherman is five minutes from the Interstate 5/Highway 126 interchange and within 20 minutes of eight major highways and freeways. Highway 126 offers drives to the Port of Hueneme in an hour and 10 minutes, and Interstate 5, the main north/south freeway running along the west coast, opens up access to the region and reaches the ports of Los Angeles and Long Beach in an hour and 45 minutes. Other nearby transportation channels include the Bob Hope Airport, a 35-minute drive, and the Union Pacific Railroad in Los Angeles, a 50-minute drive. 29003 Avenue Sherman places businesses at the core of a well-educated workforce and a thriving community, known as the best-kept secret in Southern California. This building is also available for sale at $149 per square foot.

hoodMarket: Located roughly 20 miles south of Uptown, York County benefits from Charlotte’s fast-growing population and South Carolina’s friendly industrial business climate. Drive times along Interstate 77 to the city center and the Charlotte Douglas International Airport typically come in under 30 minutes. Moving southbound, Interstate 77 provides a direct line to Columbia, South Carolina, and the Port of Charleston. The area also boasts two Class I railroads serviced by Norfolk Southern and CSX. ,As part of one of the fastest-growing metros in the U.S., York County’s workforce continues to grow. Residents here enjoy a low cost of living but still benefit from close proximity to a major Southeastern city. Pockets along Interstate 77 have seen strong increases in population, and more than 25% of these adults hold a bachelor’s degree or higher. ,While there are plenty of office and entertainment nodes here, this area is known for its industrial portfolio. Companies such as Ross, Stanley Black & Decker, U.S. Foods, Fed Ex, and DHL all have facilities in the area and employ thousands of people. Industrial properties here rent at a discount to the Charlotte average as well as heavy industrial areas near the airport and Cabarrus County.
propOverview: Riverwalk Business Park is in an ideal location for combining quality of life with business efficiency. The park is part of a 1,008-acre, master-planned community that is home to over 2,000 residential units, multiple retail destinations, 2.5 miles of riverfront, and plenty of cycling trails. These attractions provide an in-place labor force and a high quality of living for those that reside there. This unique position within a vibrant community has already attracted strong tenants to the active business park portion of the Riverwalk development. Companies like DHL Supply Chain, McKesson, Continental Tire, Atlas Copco, and NFI have already made their home there. The location of Rock Hill, SC helps serve the needs of any distribution or manufacturing company. Almost equidistant to either Miami or New York, Rock Hill offers unparalleled access to the major transportation corridors of the eastern United States. 782 Paragon Way at Riverwalk Business Park is only 1 mile to I-77, which can have drivers to the I-485 interchange near Charlotte, NC in under 15 minutes, and Charlotte Douglas International Airport (CLT) in about 36. Charlotte Douglas International Airport is unique in its freight capacity offering access to the Norfolk Southern Railway’s Charlotte Regional Intermodal Facility, the only facility of its type operating between two active runways and capable of seamlessly linking freight operations by air, rail, and truck with access to seaports. 782 Paragon Way is newly constructed within Riverwalk Business Park and features 30 loading docks, 2 drive-in doors, 32’ clear heights, 31 trailer parking spaces, and a 130’ truck court with a 50’ concrete apron. There is 5,000 square feet of dedicated office space, with room to expand. Because of its location in Riverwalk Business Park, this property is eligible for two economic development incentives. The first of which is a multi-county business park designation, providing special tax treatment on real and personal property and lowering overall tax liability. The second is textile tax credits, offering credits against state income tax liability or overall lower project costs.
